## First Solution.

Let $z_{1}=a+b i$ and $z_{2}=c+d i(a, b, c, d \in \mathbb{R})$.

The given condition $\left|z_{1}+2 z_{2}\right|=\left|2 z_{1}+z_{2}\right|$ is equivalent to:

$$
\begin{aligned}
|(a+b i)+2(c+d i)| & =|2(a+b i)+(c+d i)| \\
|(a+2 c)+(b+2 d) i| & =|(2 a+c)+(2 b+d) i| \\
(a+2 c)^{2}+(b+2 d)^{2} & =(2 a+c)^{2}+(2 b+d)^{2} \\
a^{2}+4 a c+4 c^{2}+b^{2}+4 b d+4 d^{2} & =4 a^{2}+4 a c+c^{2}+4 b^{2}+4 b d+d^{2} \\
3 c^{2}+3 d^{2} & =3 a^{2}+3 b^{2} \\
a^{2}+b^{2} & =c^{2}+d^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let $\alpha \in \mathbb{R}$. Multiplying the above equality by $1-\alpha^{2}$, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(1-\alpha^{2}\right) a^{2}+\left(1-\alpha^{2}\right) b^{2} & =\left(1-\alpha^{2}\right) c^{2}+\left(1-\alpha^{2}\right) d^{2} \\
a^{2}+\alpha^{2} c^{2}+b^{2}+\alpha^{2} d^{2} & =\alpha^{2} a^{2}+c^{2}+\alpha^{2} b^{2}+d^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, add $2 \alpha a c+2 \alpha b d$ to both sides of the equality:

$$
\begin{aligned}
a^{2}+2 \alpha a c+\alpha^{2} c^{2}+b^{2}+2 \alpha b d+\alpha^{2} d^{2} & =\alpha^{2} a^{2}+2 \alpha a c+c^{2}+\alpha^{2} b^{2}+2 \alpha b d+d^{2} \\
(a+\alpha c)^{2}+(b+\alpha d)^{2} & =(\alpha a+c)^{2}+(\alpha b+d)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally,

$$
\begin{aligned}
|(a+\alpha c)+(b+\alpha d) i| & =|(\alpha a+c)+(\alpha b+d) i| \\
|(a+b i)+\alpha(c+d i)| & =|\alpha(a+b i)+(c+d i)|
\end{aligned}
$$

which is $\left|z_{1}+\alpha z_{2}\right|=\left|\alpha z_{1}+z_{2}\right|$, as required.

